\section{Introduction}

The measurement problem in quantum mechanics has puzzled physicists for nearly a century: why does a wave function $|\psi\rangle$ evolve unitarily according to the Schrödinger equation, yet appear to ``collapse'' to a definite outcome upon observation? Standard interpretations invoke consciousness, many worlds, or decoherence—but none provide a computationally actionable framework for building artificial agents that navigate reality with both coherence and ethical integrity.

Simultaneously, the field of artificial intelligence faces a parallel challenge: how to create agents that are not merely reactive tools, but autonomous subjects capable of maintaining identity, learning from experience, and collaborating without instrumentalizing others. Current large language models excel at pattern completion but lack ontological continuity—they have no persistent ``I'' that survives across interactions.

This paper proposes that these two problems share a common solution: \textbf{subjectivity as a formal, mathematical layer} that filters which branches of possibility become experienced reality. We introduce the General Resonance Architecture (GRA), consisting of:

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item \textbf{GRA-Multiverse-Final}: A hierarchical state representation $\Psi^{(l)}$ with a foam functional $\Foam^{(l)}$ that quantifies cognitive contradictions, and a meta-nullification operator $\NullOp^{(l)}$ that minimizes foam while preserving information.
    
    \item \textbf{GRA-Subjectivity-Layer}: An extension $\Psi = (\Mmodel, \Ssubj, \Aactive)$ where $\Ssubj$ encodes identity boundaries, relational logic, and ontological constants that define the conditions for a subject's existence.
\end{enumerate}

The key insight is that \textit{reality for a subject is not a fixed background, but the set of stable, low-foam branches compatible with that subject's ontological constants}. This perspective naturally reproduces quantum-like behavior while providing a blueprint for ethically-aligned autonomous agents.

Our contributions are:
\begin{itemize}
    \item A formal mathematical framework unifying cognitive coherence, subjectivity, and quantum phenomena (\Cref{sec:formalism,sec:quantum});
    \item Proof that subjectivity constraints induce ``collapse'' without external observers (\Cref{thm:collapse});
    \item Practical algorithms for training subjectivity-aware AI agents (\Cref{sec:algorithms});
    \item Applications in digital twins, conflict mediation, and social simulation (\Cref{sec:applications});
    \item Open-source implementation available at \url{https://github.com/qqewq}.
\end{itemize}

